Owner: Legal / Security
Approved By: CEO

1. Purpose
This policy defines how long Kahana retains different types of data and how that data is securely deleted or anonymized when it is no longer needed. The goal is to:

Meet legal, contractual, and business requirements.

Protect customer and company data from unnecessary exposure.

Support privacy principles and SOC 2 controls.

2. Scope
This policy applies to:

All data processed, stored, or transmitted by Kahana in relation to Kahana Oasis, including:

Customer workspace content and files.

Customer account and billing data.

Logs and telemetry.

Internal operational and HR data.

All storage locations: production systems, backups, logs, local devices (where applicable), and third‑party systems managed by Kahana.

All Kahana employees, contractors, and vendors handling this data.

3. Data Categories
Kahana groups data into high‑level categories. Concrete durations can be finalized with Legal; below are reasonable defaults you can adjust.

Customer Workspace Data and Files

Content created or uploaded by customers into Kahana hubs/workspaces.

Customer Account and Billing Data

Account profiles, subscription info, payment‑related records (but not full card data, which is handled by payment processors).

System and Security Logs

Application logs, audit logs, access logs, infrastructure logs.

Support and Communication Records

Support tickets, emails, chat transcripts with customers.

Internal Operational Data

Product analytics, internal documents, project/task records.

HR and Personnel Data

Employee records, contracts, performance, and training records.

Backups and Snapshots

Copies of any of the above stored as part of the backup program.

4. Default Retention Periods (Suggested Baseline)
You can adjust these with Legal and based on customer commitments:

Customer Workspace Data and Files

Retention:

While the customer account is active.

After account termination: retained for 30–90 days grace period for restoration, then deleted or anonymized.

Customers may request earlier deletion where permitted by law and contract.

Customer Account and Billing Data

Retention:

While account is active.

After termination: retained for 3–7 years to comply with financial, tax, and contractual obligations.

Certain data may be anonymized instead of fully deleted where appropriate.

System and Security Logs

Retention:

Security/audit logs: 12–24 months target; current Supabase Pro = 7-day retention (document current state; consider Log Drains for extended retention).

Less critical logs: 3–6 months depending on value and cost.

Support and Communication Records

Retention: 2–3 years from last interaction, or longer if needed for dispute handling or legal obligations.

Internal Operational Data

Retention: based on business need and other policies (e.g., until replaced or superseded, subject to periodic review).

HR and Personnel Data

Retention:

During employment.

After employment ends: retained for 3–7 years or as required by labor and tax laws.

Backups and Snapshots

Retention:

Supabase: Pro = 7 days, Team = 14 days, Enterprise = 30 days. See Backup and Restoration Policy for details.

Older backups automatically expired/overwritten.

If law, contract, or a specific customer agreement requires different retention, that requirement overrides these defaults for the relevant data.

5. Legal Holds and Exceptions
If Legal determines that certain data is needed for an ongoing or reasonably anticipated investigation, dispute, or legal matter, a legal hold may be placed on that data.

While a legal hold is in effect, normal deletion processes for that data are suspended.

Once the hold is lifted, data resumes following normal retention/destruction timelines.

6. Secure Destruction and Anonymization
When data reaches the end of its retention period (and is not subject to a legal hold), it must be securely destroyed or anonymized:

Application / Database Data

Deleted via application or database processes so that it is no longer accessible.

For structured data, rows/records are deleted or irreversibly anonymized (removing identifiers linking to individuals/organizations).

Object / File Storage

Files are deleted via storage controls (e.g., deleting objects from buckets).

Where storage uses versioning, ensure that old versions are also removed per retention rules.

Backups

Deletion is normally achieved by backup expiration: backups exceeding their configured retention period are automatically deleted or overwritten.

Kahana does not perform per‑record deletion inside historical backups unless required by law; instead, data is removed from live systems and then naturally leaves backups as they age out.

Physical Media (if any)

Any physical media (disks, drives) must be destroyed or wiped using industry‑standard methods if decommissioned.

7. Customer Requests and Privacy Rights
Where applicable law or contract grants customers or end‑users specific data rights (e.g., access, deletion):

Kahana will provide mechanisms for customers to request:

Deletion of their account data and related personal data, subject to legal retention requirements.

Export or access to certain data.

When honoring deletion requests:

Live systems are updated to remove or anonymize the requested data.

Backups are not modified individually; instead, the data will disappear as backups age out, and those backups are only used for restore in limited cases.

Legal and Security must ensure that responses to such requests align with applicable regulations (e.g., GDPR, if relevant, or local law).

8. Data Ownership and Responsibilities
Data Owners (e.g., Product, Support, HR, Finance):

Classify their data and confirm that retention periods meet business and legal needs.

Periodically review data stores for relevance and clean‑up opportunities.

Legal / Compliance:

Define minimum retention requirements based on law and contract.

Advise on legal holds and exceptions.

Security / DevOps / Engineering:

Implement technical enforcement (e.g., automatic deletion jobs, backup retention).

Ensure deletion/anonymization methods are effective and secure.

9. Documentation and Automation
Wherever possible, retention and deletion should be implemented via:

Automated jobs (e.g., scheduled deletion tasks, lifecycle rules in storage).

Configuration of backup retention within cloud services.

Procedures for manual deletion (e.g., special cases, legal requests) must be documented, including approvals and verification steps.

10. Monitoring and Verification
Periodic checks should verify that:

Deletion jobs and lifecycle rules are running as expected.

Backup retention settings match this policy.

Accumulated data does not exceed defined retention without justification.

Any issues identified (e.g., data not being deleted as expected) must be investigated and remediated.

11. Violations and Enforcement
Failure to follow this policy (e.g., retaining data indefinitely without justification, deleting data that must be retained, mishandling deletion requests) may result in disciplinary action.

Serious or willful violations may also lead to legal or contractual consequences.

12. Review and Maintenance
This policy must be reviewed at least annually, and whenever there are:

Significant changes in applicable laws/regulations.

Changes to Kahana’s services, data flows, or storage architecture.

Updates must be approved by Legal and Security and communicated to relevant teams.

